rmk:
Was a mystery, still sort of is. Reviewing Yap et al. in BirdingAsia and comparing the XC recordings myself, I am relatively certain that this individual is P. borealoides. This individual calls at ~4750hz. The difference in call frequency between the two species is striking ~5700hz vs ~4600hz, with very high level of significance (I used Audacity, Excel, t-test). Unfortunately the number of unequivocal recordings on or near breeding grounds which I used for comparison was a mere 6 individual birds for Pale-legged on the mainland and 6 for Sakhalin in Japan plus the Singapore record XC163797. 

A couple of exceptions: XC208869 is a recording on migration of an agitated bird that seems to have made call of both species. If they are the same individual, XC78272 & XC78273, also produced the call of both species. 

We need to do more recording in order to differentiate these with a greater degree of certainty.
